					<div class="content-intro-text">
						<h1>Innovation Systems for Smallholder Farming</h1>
													<p class="author"><strong>Author:</strong>
								Judith Ann Francis, CTA</p>
																								
													<p class="date"><strong>Date:</strong>
							20/07/2007</p>
																									<p class="intro">Introduction:</p>
							 <p>







 




  
  

	
	<a href="/var/knowledge/storage/images/media/images/logos/eec_eu2007de_donors/141204-1-eng-GB/eec_eu2007de_donors.jpg" rel="lightbox[]" >	
	  </a>
	
	
	
	
  	






	 
  





	 </p> <p>Today, innovation is often defined as the development, adaptation or imitation and the subsequent adoption of technologies or the application of knowledge that is new within a specific context. It is seen as an interactive process, in which enterprises, in continuous interaction with each other and supported by institutions and organizations innovate and bring new products, processes and services into social and economic use. Taking this perspective, there is a need for changing our general perception of smallholder farmers who are often described as a poor, ignorant, illiterate persons, resistant to change and unwilling to adopt new ideas and technologies. Whereas in reality, they are resilient and enterprising – risk takers, who have context specific knowledge of their environment and are willing to adopt new ideas, knowledge and technology, especially if they respond to their specific needs and add value to their circumstances. Read more… <i>Paper presented at the 2nd European Forum on Sustainable Development, Berlin, Germany, 18-21 June 2007</i>. </p>
						
						
						
						<br/>&nbsp;
					</div> 
					<br class="cl">
				</div> 
				 
			
				<div id="content-item">
											<div class="box-content">
							<a class="storylist" href="/layout/set/print/content/view/full/5045">Print</a>
																				</div> 
						<br class="cl">
		
					 
	
				</div> 
			
				<div id="main-content" class="content view">					

	                          
			

	<!-- BEGIN BODY TEXT -->	
	
			<div class="stdtext">	
			
 <p>'Farmers are keen learners but they do not in all circumstances accept technological inputs from external sources' (Isubikalu, 2007). How then can smallholder farmers be supported to build on their social and cultural traditions and practices to create or adapt and integrate new knowledge? How can their skills for analysis, information search and decision-making be developed / enhanced?</p> <p>A system of innovation consists of a network of actors who together with the institutions and policies that influence their innovative behaviour create, diffuse and use knowledge within an economic framework. The system actors include:the enterprises (e.g. farms and other agro related enterprises), commodity and industry associations, innovation and productivity centres, standard setting bodies, research and development organizations, universities, education and vocational training centres and information and financial services among others. It is dynamic and the performance of the various actors and as such, the system as a whole, is determined by the habits, practices and competencies of the actors.</p> <p>The most important element for the success of an innovation system is the learning capacity of individuals, groups, organizations, countries. How can the smallholder farmer become the central focus of the agricultural innovation system? Will his/her capacity to learn and innovate be recognized and facilitated to contribute to achieving the MDGs? How can governments and organizations promote a culture of innovation? How can they build local capacity to facilitate continuous learning to sustain innovation? In all other enterprises, the consumer is profiled before a new technology; product or service is developed and marketed. A need must exist for the new knowledge or technology if there is to be uptake. Demand-driven modes of innovation for the smallholder farmers, suggest that they experience common problems. This is generally not the case because of socio-economic and other constraints including land ownership and vagaries of climate, water and soil. Relevance, utility and adaptability are important issues for smallholder farmers, as new technologies (e.g. seeds or equipment) must be within their economic reach and perform effectively under varied environmental conditions. Lessons can be learned from the rapid spread of cell phones in Africa (e.g. in Nigeria the number of mobile phone subscribers jumped from 370,000 in 2001 to 16.8 million in 2005) or from farmers’ adoption of crops (e.g. Nerica rice, the production of which has increased for the 6th consecutive year in West Africa and is now spreading to East Africa). Both technologies offered rural populations opportunities for increasing access to information, markets and improving household income.</p> <p>More genuine engagement with smallholder farmers is needed to understand their specific needs and for their demands to be clearly expressed. All actors in the innovation system have knowledge and by respecting this principle and creating platforms for trust to be established, the exchange and uptake of ideas, knowledge and experiences by system actors can be facilitated. Including smallholder farmers in this process and demonstrating respect for their values and knowledge will contribute to ensuring that their needs and special circumstances influence the research agenda. Public research and extension systems in developing countries are under-resourced. In Uganda, the ratio of extension staff to farmers is 1:500 (Isubikalu, 2007). The R&amp;D budget for the whole of sub-Saharan Africa is 1,461 million US$ which is app. onetenth the budget for High Income Countries (Pardey et al., 2006). Reform is urgently needed. The changes in the global trading environment, the growing importance of science, technology and innovation (ST&amp;I) for socio-economic development and the opportunities provided by the rapid advances in ICTs to share information and knowledge, suggest that as a matter of priority, financial resources should be made available to upgrade physical infrastructure and to attract, retain and retrain staff. Developing countries must be encouraged and supported to build endogenous ST&amp;I capacity for development (Mashelkar, 2005).</p> <p>The private sector engages in research collaboration if there is profit to be made and will partner with public organizations in which they have confidence. Strong public partners are necessary for mutually beneficial relationships. Private sector research capacity can be harnessed by building the credibility of national institutions to conduct cutting edge and relevant and timely research. Public partners must also be proactive and rules must be established to ensure that both partners benefit from the relationship. </p> <p>Intellectual Property Rights (IPRs) are both a hindrance and a trigger for agricultural innovations. Technologies may be placed outside the reach of poor farmers if costs are prohibitive or the use may be restrictive e.g. Gene Use Restricted Technology (GURT) will negatively impact on farmers’ traditional practice of reusing seeds with possible unforeseen social consequences. On the other hand, IPRs provide opportunities for local communities to benefit from their indigenous knowledge if legal guidance and technical support are available. Creating balance between providing incentives for private investment in research and making technologies available for the poor is possible if public knowledge systems are strengthened. National governments and institutions must show visionary leadership. </p> <p>Development strategies should respond to the changing paradigms and support programmes that emphasize building and retooling national systems. Criteria must be established for international organizations to demonstrate in tangible terms how national systems will benefit and how these in turn respond to the needs of the poor. Donors and governments can invest in programmes at the level of policy, education and training, research and development, market systems, micro-credit, information services and empowerment of smallholder farmers through coordinated complementary actions. The changing context within which innovation occurs is extremely challenging and can be facilitated if national and international partners are willing to learn and change.</p> <p><b>References</b> </p> 
<ul>
 
<li> Isubikalu, P. (2007) Stepping Stones to Improve upon Functioning of Participatory </li>
 
<li> Agricultural Extension Programmes: Farmer Field Schools in Uganda. Wageningen Academic Publishers, The Netherlands. ISBN: 978-90-8686-021-0. </li>
 
<li> Mahelkar, R.A. (2005) Nation Building through Science &amp; Technology: A Developing World Perspective. Innovations Strategy. 1.1:16-32. </li>
 
<li> Pardey, G. P., Beintema, N., Dehmer, S. &amp; Wood, S. 2006. Agricultural research:A Growing Divide? International Food Policy Research Institute, Washington D.C. </li>
 
</ul>

		</div>
		
	<!-- END BODY TEXT -->
		
			
		
	
	
			
				

		<strong class="date_small">20/07/2007</strong>
